    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-08-19T14:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-08-19T14:45:00-05:00" n="360"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d360">
                <head>360. Memorandum of a Conversation, Department of State, Washington, August 19,
                    1957, 3:45 p.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d360fn1">Source: Department of
                        State, <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>
                        Files: Lot 66 D 123. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_HF1"
                            >Howe</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1957-08-19T15:45:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 19, 1957, 3:45 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PRESENT</head>
                    <item>[Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>]</item>
                    <item>The Under Secretary</item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MRD1"
                            >Murphy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_O1">O</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HLW1"
                            >Henderson</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RWM1"
                            >Rountree</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RSW1"
                            >Rockwell</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MJSJ1">Moose</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_RJP1">Richards</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_R1">R</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CHSJ1"
                            >Cumming</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_U1">U</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RRB1"
                            >Reams</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_S1">S</gloss>—Mr.
                            <persName corresp="#p_HF1">Howe</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>—Mr. <persName>Archie
                            Roosevelt</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>—Mr. <persName>Frank Wisner</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>-General <persName corresp="#p_CLGCP1"
                            >Cabell</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName> reviewed for the Secretary
                    the situation as it has developed over the course of last week, including the
                    PNG of the US officials and the most recent take-over by the Communist Chief of
                    Staff.</p>
                <p>He then reviewed the possible courses of action in the current situation along
                    the general lines of the enclosed “talking paper.”<note n="2" xml:id="d360fn2">A
                        notation on the source text indicates that the document was destroyed on
                        August 22.</note>
                </p>
                <p>In the hour-long discussion which ensued, the various aspects of the problem were
                    gone over thoroughly, including particularly an appraisal of the various
                    personalities presently involved in the situation or who might be involved. The
                    attitudes and possible actions by the various other Middle Eastern countries was
                    also canvassed. No action resulted other than for the Secretary to ask Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWM1">Rountree</persName> to prepare for him, the
                    Secretary, to review a briefing statement on the Syrian problem for the
                    President’s press conference.</p>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> representatives discussed the situation
                    as they saw it… .</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_RJP1">Richards</persName> cautioned not to move
                    too fast in a situation which might well change character and ease off in a few
                    days or weeks.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MJSJ1">Moose</persName> noted that while the
                    situation was very serious, the most powerful man in Syria, Serraj, was still in
                    place and apparently not yet touched by the new regime.</p>
                <pb facs="0673" n="641" xml:id="pg_641"/>
                <p>. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>The Secretary concluded that we must view the situation as wholly unacceptable.
                    This did not mean that any particular course of action should be taken either
                    immediately or in the next weeks but that all of our effort should be directed
                    on the basis that we could not afford to have exist a Soviet satellite not
                    contiguous to the Soviet border and in the midst of the already delicate Middle
                    East situation. He also agreed that we should capitalize on the present alarm
                    felt by our friends over the situation in Syria, an alarm which tends to subside
                    over a period of time. We could not consider that time is on our side and we
                    should be particularly careful that more violent action, especially on the part
                    of Israel, was not precipitated.</p>
            </div>
